Question 1

Letâs begin by fitting a model where wage_percent_of_male is the outcome variable and the explanatory variables are year and major_category. As we learned in our previous homework, we should always relevel categorical variables with more than one category in order to be sure what the model output is telling us. So letâs do that first. Letâs make âManagement, Business, and Financialâ the reference category. Our results will be in comparison to this group.

gender_employment <- gender_employment %>% 
  mutate(major_category = as.factor(major_category), 
         major_category = relevel(major_category, ref = "Management, Business, and Financial"))

Can we say anything about overall trends by year?

##You have to multiply the slope (0.192) by the year.

Interpreting models with multiple categorical variables is not that much different than the examples presented in the book. Here, we have 8 major categories. Adding this explanatory variable is equivalent to adding 7 variables to the model, each of which records whether our occupation belongs to the given category. This is easier to see when written down as an equation. Our line of best fit here could be written as:

Å· = Î²0 + Î²1 x year + Î²2 x occ2 + Î²3 x occ3â¦ Î²8 x occ7

So each coefficient of our model is associated with a binary variable that is either 0 or 1 and that indicates membership in an occupation group with a 1. You can think about these coefficients as switches; they are turned on when they are 1, they are turned off when they are 0. Because an occupation only belongs to one category at any time, it has a 1 for one of those values and a zero on all other ones. Multiplying anything by 0 makes it 0 - the betas for the categories to which our occupation does not belong then get turned off, being multiplied by 0. The only switch that stays on is the one that has a 1 - i.e.Â the category under which our occupation falls.

Let me give you an example. âChief Executivesâ belongs to the category âManagement, Business, and Financialâ. Thus, this observation has a 0 for all other dummy variables for category membership and those betas will play no role in estimating our value. Wait, but in your model output thereâs no coefficient for âManagement, Business, and Financialâ. Thatâs because thatâs our reference category; it is baked into beta 0, the intercept. This is also why I said that adding a categorical variable of 8 categories implies adding 7 coefficients. You get the extra one for free because thatâs your reference category. The betas then will tell you how much categories differ from your reference group.

Okay, that was a lot. Now you do some interpretation. Using the coefficients from your model, calculate the wage percentage of male income for Sales and Office occupations on 2015.

##-306.718 + 3.326 = -303.392

##Å· = -303.392 + 0.192 x 2015

##Å· = 83.488

##The wage percentage of male income for Sales and Office occupations in 2015 is 83.488.

Now calculate the wage percentage of male income for Service occupations on 2016.

##-306.718 + 6.077 = -300.641

##Å· = -300.641 + 0.192 x 2016

##Å· = 86.431

##The wage percentage of male income for Service occupations in 2016 is 86.431.

Question 2

The model above assumes parallel trends. This means that we are telling the model to draw a line for each major category, and let the lines start at different points but make the slopes the same. The only thing that changes across major categories then is the intercept of the lines.

Letâs check if this assumption is warranted. Using the code from the introductory section, make a similar plot but facet it by major category so that lines vary across categories.

gender_employment %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = wage_percent_of_male, group = major_category, color = major_category)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.1) +
  labs(title = "Women's Percentage of Male Earnings by Year and Major Category", x = "Year", y = "Women's Percentage of Male Earnings") +
  geom_parallel_slopes(se = FALSE) +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

What do you notice? Is the parallel trends assumption warranted?

##Yes, the lines are parallel.

Letâs think a bit about what this model says with an equation. We are doubling our coefficients: we have betas for 7 of 8 categories and betas for their respective interaction. Our equation would look something like this:

Å· = Î²0 + Î²1 x year + Î²2 x occ2 + Î²3 x occ3â¦ Î²8 x occ7 + Î²9 x occ2 x year + Î²10 x occ3 x yearâ¦ Î²16 x occ7 x year

What does this mean? Occupation 2 in our case is âComputer, Engineering, and Scienceâ. For this occupation, then, only four betas are âswitched onâ: beta 0, beta 1, beta 2, and beta 9. If we want to calculate our estimate for the âComputer, Engineering, and Scienceâ, for 2016, we would do the following:

Å· = Î²0 + Î²1 x 2016 + Î²2 + Î²9 x 2016

So tell me what the estimate would be for âComputer, Engineering, and Scienceâ for 2016. What about the same estimate but for âServiceâ? Do you notice any differences?

Letâs add the other variable in there. We want a model that takes into account the variable percent_female. The thinking behind this addition is that the proportion of women in an industry might affect how much the gender paygap has changed across the last few years.

Before we build the model we want to explore the relationship between these variables. Like in the chapter, use select() and cor() to find the correlations between these three variables. Because we have some missing values, you want to give cor() the argument use = "complete.obs".

Question 6

Here, we will practice some model comparison and I will also introduce you to another useful tool from the broom package.

First, letâs review the discussion about R squared. Briefly tell me, in your own words, what R squared is.

##R squared tells us how much of the variation in y is explained by our model.

Okay, letâs now compare the R squared for simple_fit and multiple_fit. To do this we are going to use glance() from the broom package. Run glance() on simple_fit. This should give you a lot of information, including the R squared. It turns out that you can save that output doing something like this.

simple_glanced <- glance(simple_fit)

And then you can access the R squared, the same way you would access a column from a dataframe, with the $ sign.

simple_glanced$r.squared
[1] 0.0005778711

Do this for both models and compare the R squared.

multiple_glanced <- glance(multiple_fit)
multiple_glanced$r.squared
[1] 0.01321338

What can you conclude from this?

##For simple_fit, 0.5% of the variance in y is explained by the model. For multiple_fit, 1% of the variance in y is explained by the model.

A Warning Sign

Now, I want to tell you a cautionary tale about R squared. While a useful metric, R squared has one big weakness: it improves when you add any variable to your model, regardless of how nonsensical it is. This is because R squared just takes into account the amount of variance explained and even random noise will be able to account for some variation. Letâs see this in action. I am going to create a vector of random values the same size as our dataframe.

random_numbers <- rnorm(n = nrow(gender_employment), 
                        mean = 0, 
                        sd = 4)

Now, I will add this column and put it into our model:

gender_employment$random_noise <- random_numbers

# New model 
random_fit <- lm(wage_percent_of_male ~ year + percent_female + random_noise, data = gender_employment)

Examine the R squared for yourself and consider the implications of this little exercise!
